               <msContents>
                  <summary>Perhaps the Life of the ascete Hermine, native of Pemje (el-Behnasa) and Bishop of Huw (Diospolis Parva, Diospolis Mikra) in Upper Egypt, a contemporary of Athanasius, Patriarch of Alexandria (d. 373 A.D.). Hair side, col. 2: (Apa Herminah?) conquers the Contender in Christ, angels mentioned; Flesh side, Apa Hermina contends with the devil (diabolos), angel(s?) mntioned. See Coptic Synaxarium 2 Choiak (28 November) for epitome of Hermine, native of Pemje (el-Behnasa) and Bishop of Huw (Diospolis Parva, Diospolis Mikra) in Upper Egypt, and contemporary of Athanasius, Patriarch of Alexandria (d. 373).</summary>
                  <msItem>
                     <note type="general">Margins: Hair side: left, 2 cm.; bottom, 5 cm.; right, 3 cm.; Flesh side: left, 2.5 cm.; bottom, 4 cm.; right, 1 cm.</note>
                     <note type="lines">Hair side: 2 cols. (col. 1, 14 lines; col. 2, 17 lines); Flesh side: 2 cols. (col. 1: 17 lines; col. 2, 16 lines)</note>
                     <note type="recto_verso">Text continues from hair side to flesh side</note>
                     <textLang mainLang="egy-Copt">Coptic (Bohairic?)</textLang>
                  </msItem>
